{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657499/1924030901/0212.xml":{"full_text":".OLDFIELDIN FAVOR\nOF BALLOON TIRES\nTells of Trip Through Mud\nto California\u2014Praises Per\nformance of Equipment.\nGaston Chevrolet, the idol of auto\nmobile race enthusiasts before his\ndeath several years ago. won the\nI>ar.i mount victory of his racing ca\n,r<,or the international 500-mile\nsweepstake race at Indianapolis\u2014-on\ntires which carried comparatively\nlow air pressure. This was in 1920.\n\u25a0ttnd since then many of the leading'\nrace drivers have reduced the air\n*>-pressure in their tires as much as\npossible, and have ridden \"on air\u201d in\ne the itreat speed tests.\nThis interesting and timely dis\nclosure was made by Barney Oldfield.\ntdean of race drivers, in recent letters\nto Harvey S. Firestone, president of\ntho Firestone Tire and Rubber Com\npany of Akron. Ohio, ami Howard O.\nMarmon, vice president and chief en-\nKjne.-r of tlie Nordyke and Marmon\nCompany of Indianapolis, manufac\nturers of Marmon automobiles. Old\nfield\u2019s letters both are strong indorse\nments of balloon tires. They describe\nhis last cross-continent trip in his\n.Marmon coupe equipped with balloon\ntires.\nItuftlcil Mud Without Chains.\n\u201cI left Akron under the most ad-\nverso weather and road conditions for\nthe Facific coast, and 1 battled mud\nand inclement weather the entire dis\ntance to I-os Angeles,*\u2019 the famous\nracing engineer said in his letter to\nMr, Firestone.\n\"The first day out I made approxi\nmately SOO miles in the mud. The\nsecond day I again battled the mud\nlor a distance of 300 miles. The\nthird day 1 made only \"00 miles in the\nmud. The fourth day 1 encounteftd\nmountains and desert roads. Arriv-,\nlug in El Faso. X found that my odo- 1\nmeter had registered 200 miles more\nthan tho distance scheduled on tho\nmaps of the different routes which I\nfollowed. This was due to the fact\ntitpt I did not use chains. Cotisc- I\nfluently, my rear wheels were spin\nning in 4h\u00ab mud. All of this distance\nwas negotiated without chains, and I\npassed many cars going in the same\ndirection that were equipped with\nohains and were having great diffi\nculty making any progress at all.\n\"In the sandy desert roads I could\npull out of the roads and go around\ncars in the soft sand. This I was\nnever able to do before with the ordi\nnary high-pressure tires. On my ar\nrival ih Los Angelos my odometer\nshowed a total of 2,120 miles.\n\u201cI found that my car was In perfect\nCondition, after the roughest cross\ncountry driving X have ever done. I\n\u00aban heartily recommend balloon tires\nafter their marvelous performance on\nthis trip.\u201d\nA brief study of the records shows\nthat Barney Oldfield has been a\nstanch advocate of low-air-pressure\ntires for many years. As far back as\nt.ho \u201cUos Angeles-to-Phoenix. desert\nrace.\u201d which was won by Oldfield\nalong with the title of -master driver\nof the world, Oldfield believed in rid\ning on air. In this classic he used\nfabric tires with two extra pli\u00ab\u00a3 and\ncarried thirty pounds of air pressure\nin the front tires and thirty-five in\ntho rear.\nU. S. AUTO EXPORTS PUT\nAT $135,000,000 IN 1923:\n\nPorty Per Cent Increase Over;\n1922\u2014L0w-Priced Cars\nBest Sellers.\nt i\nApproximately $135,000,0ut' worth of j\nautomobiles, both passenger cars and\ntrucks, together with parts, were ex- j\nported from this country in 1923.\nThis was an increase of about 40\nper cent over exports for 1922. In-\ndications point to an even larger ex- 1\nport business during the coming year, i\naccording to Thomas O\u2019Brien, assist\nant general sales manager of the Olds\nMotor Works. Bansing, Mich.\n\u201cEconomically. Europe is not in any\nconsiderable degree belter off than it\nwas a year ago,\" said Mr. O\u2019Brien.\n\"Other parts of the world are in fair\nshape, according to reports. But trade\nwith all countries is strongly influ- j\nenced by the relatively high price of i\nthe American dollar. For that reason,\nthe automobile that sells under SI,OOO\nwill be tho ear that\" has the best\nchance to increase its export busi- I\nness.^\n\"Export figures for tlie past few\nyears prove that the great demand in\nother countries Is for cars costing\nless than SI,OOO. In 1922, there were\nexported from the United States 42,-\n\"27 automobiles selling for SBOO or\nless, valued at $20,503,025. During the\npame period there were exported\n\u00a32.513 cars costing between 1800 and\n52.000, and 2.027 cars above the $2,000\n\"Exact figures for 1923 have net j\nbeen compiled as yet, but conserve- j\nrive estimates taken from the sta- J\nliatics available indicate that exports\nfor the past year will approximate\n40,000 cars costing up to SBOO each,\nHI.OOO cars costing from SBOO to $2,000 j\nvach and 2,400 cars in classes above\n52.000. The total value of passenger\ncars exported during 1923 is esti- J\nmated at $75,000,000, as compared with\nthe $51,039,335 for 1923.\nReports from the General Motors\ntExport Company indicate that the j\npopular feeling in favor of American 1\ncars is growing abroad, and that this j\nfield is most promising. The largest\ndemand is for an automobile that will i\noperate smoothly, yet economically.\nstnd one not unduly expensive.\n\u201cRarely does business depression\nextend throughout the world. There\nfore, if manufacturers in this country\nacquire foreign business, it is an In\nsurance against any depression in\nthis country that might be caused by\ncrop failures or similar unavoidable\nv asons. A good foreign trade would 1\nxuean that American workmen would j\nhe kept employed during any tern-\nporary business lull, and this in Itself\n\u2022would tend to shorten the life of any I\n\u2022rich depression period.\u201d\nARMY PIONEER IN AUTO.\nSignal Corps Adopted Motor Care i\nin 1899\u2014Ended Public Skepticism-1\nIt was in 1899 that the United\nelates Army Signal Corps placed the\n(stamp of practicality upon the auto\nmobile by adopting its use. No one\nthing could have done more to con\nvince a then doubting public that the j\nmotor car had come\u2019to stay and would\nplay a big part in transportation. j\nWATEE MAY HELP OH. j\nIf the engine\u2019s oil supply ever j\nruns tow, and there is no fresh oil j\navailable, the driver is Justified in i\ntrying to limp to a garage by diluting j\nDie oil with water. Ol! floats on wa\nter, which means that when the ri!lx\nture is pumped to the oil troughs the\ndippers at the ends of the connecting!\nrods will pick up the oil which floats\non the top. This will often enable i\nthe engine to continue running. With- i\nout the water the oil would not bo i\nsufficient to go the rounds of the sys\ntem, thus leaving some vital spot\nwithout any sort of lubricant at all. I\nU. S. USES MANY CABS.\nA fine fleet of motor cars la now aj\naccessary part of the national govern- j\nment equipment. Prior to William\nMcKinley\u2019s administration only horse\ndrawn carriages were used. McKinley i\nindorsed the automobile.\nPLAN 300.000 AUTOS.\nWith the announcement of a total\nTreduction of 22.018 cars amounting\nto a net volume of $17,638,400, in\nJanuary. VEMMys-Ovoi land has mad:\nf, start\" toward tfie realization of its\ngoal of 509.000 Willys-Knights and\nto be produced during 1921.^,\n;l DIRECTORY OF CURRENT DELIVERED PRICES\nON YOUR FAVORITE MOTOR CAR\n\nDuring the past year many changes have taken place in the standard makes of motor cars. All prices include the actual\ni\nAutomobile industry. Sales records have been broken \u2014Motor delivery in Washington, including war tax and delivery charges.\nCar values have increased in general in the new models. For convenience, the various makes have been arranged in an\nThe Automobile Dealers below present the current prices on alphabetical order, according to the names of cars.\ni\nApperson Brack Cadillac Chrysler Columbia Chandler Prices r Chevrol